From 79dd54a1da7409b83449f193246e94c34b84714f Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Josh Bailey <josh@vandervecken.com>
Date: Sat, 20 Jun 2026 01:11:52 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] log: flush before close in log_file_close to fix
 use-after-free

log_file_close() called fclose(log_file) and then fflush(log_file) on the
same FILE*, reading and writing freed memory. When the log file is not
stdout (the default log file, or an explicit -logfile target) fclose frees
the FILE struct and the following fflush touches it, corrupting glibc's
malloc tcache. The corruption surfaces later as a crash in an unrelated
malloc - e.g. the fopen() that loads the SID file in try_uncompress_lynx()
- so vsid segfaults intermittently (heap-layout/ASLR dependent).

Flush while the stream is still open, then close. fclose already flushes,
so the explicit flush only matters for the stdout case (which is never
closed).

Co-Authored-By: Claude Opus 4.8 (1M context) <noreply@anthropic.com>
---
 src/log.c | 2 +-
 1 file changed, 1 insertion(+), 1 deletion(-)

diff --git a/src/log.c b/src/log.c
index 1bbb89c..aceb5cc 100644
--- a/src/log.c
+++ b/src/log.c
@@ -171,10 +171,10 @@ static void log_file_close(void)
 {
     DBG(("log_file_close %p\n", log_file));
     if (log_file) {
+        fflush(log_file);
         if (log_file != stdout) {
             fclose(log_file);
         }
-        fflush(log_file);
         log_file = NULL;
     }
 }
